This non-interventional post-marketing study (H3E-US-B001) case regards a 56-year-old African American male. 
Medical history included gastrointestinal (GI) bleeding, chronic pain, deep vein thrombosis, coronary artery disease, 
hypertension (chronically overmedicated), chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, congestive heart failure, 
degenerative disc disease (lumbar 5 - sacral 1), diabetes mellitus, chronic anemia, hypoxia, and a limited infection 
of the left upper lobe. Concomitant medications included folic acid, vitamin B12, dexamethasone, 
fluticasone/salmeterol, acetylsalicylic acid, carvedilol, colchicine, escitalopram, megestrol, oxycodone 
hydrochloride, oxycodone hydrochloride/paracetamol, senna alexandrina, warfarin, tizanidine, and gabapentin. On 
31Jul08, the patient first received pemetrexed disodium (Alimta) 500 mg/m2 intravenously (IV), for the treatment of 
non-small cell lung cancer. Prior to the event, pemetrexed was last received on 02Oct08, Laboratory values 
included white blood cell count (WBC) 6.0, hemoglobin (Hgb) 9.2, platelet count (Plt) 165, and red blood cell count 
(RBC) 2.63. Onallipindays after last receiving pemetrexed, the patient was admitted to the hospital after 
sudden loss of consciousness and being found unresponsive in his home by his sister. He presented with hypoxia, 
hypotension (blood pressure 73/50, improving to 109/78), hypokalemia, thrombocytopenia, and leukopenia. 
Laboratory values included WBC 4.2, Hgb 9.2, Plt 23, RBC 2.75, potassium 2.8, and creatinine 1.23. 
Electrocardiogram revealed sinus rhythm with premature atrial complexes and no evidence of acute ischemia 
though there were some inverted T-waves in the lateral leads. Chest x-ray showed right basilar hilar fibrotic 
changes with right sided lung volume loss with trachea shift. Brain scan showed no acute intracranial abnormality. 
His blood pressure medications were held. On NM his hypotension resolved (blood pressure 132/81). He 
had worsened anemia. Laboratory values included WBC 2.9, Hgb 7.4, Plt 13, and international normalized ratio 
2.4. His opiate levels of 300 ng/ml confirmed a narcotic overdose. Chest computerized tomogram revealed a right 
