lower lobe mass; partial consolidative opacities involving right lower lobe, total right middle lobe collapse; partial 
atelectatic consolidation right upper lobe; infection in the left upper lobe; a port/central line thrombus of right distal 
subclavian vein; and probable small hepatic hemangioma. Ona11111 the patient recovered from the narcotic 
overdose. On OM an echocardiogram revealed mild left ventricular dysfunction with ejection fraction of 35% 
to 40%; diastolic dysfunction; and mild mitral regurgitation and tricuspid regurgitation were noted. He had a right 
subclavian port infection. Blood cultures revealed gram-positive cocci (methicillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus) 
confirming sepsis. The patient was treated with vancomycin, packed red blood cells, platelets, fresh frozen plasma, 
and potassium. The port was removed without complications and the patient recovered from the sepsis. The 
admission was complicated with acute renal failure superimposed on his chronic kidney disease, associated with 
the line sepsis. The patient was also noted to have complications with a peripherally inserted central catheter which 
required surgery on his left arm. No further information was provided. On_ the patient recovered from the 
leukopenia (WBC 4.8). 0ng the patient recovered from the worsened anemia (Hgb 13.9, RBC 4.18). On 
1111111111111the patient was recovering from the thrombocytopenia (Plt 166). His potassium was 3.1 (additional labs 
are available in the source documents). The patient had seen multiple specialists and was medically stabilized. He 
was able to be discharged to an extended care facility. Study therapy continued. In the opinion of the study 
investigator, the events of hypotension, worsened anemia, thrombocytopenia, leukopenia, and sepsis were possibly 
related to pemetrexed, but not related to protocol procedures. The event of narcotic overdose was assessed as not 
related to pemetrexed or protocol procedures. The investigator stated the syncope was likely due to the 
mechanism of hypotension secondary to blood pressure medications and sepsis; anemia and diarrhea (prior to 
admission) with probable GI bleeding (prior history not mentioned in current admission medical records or 
discharge summary); and/or a possible narcotic effect. The investigator stated the pemetrexed caused the platelet 
drop and WBC drop which contributed to a GI bleed and sepsis. This case is associated with US200811005786 
and US200810000689, which are separate clinical episodes for this patient. Update 22Dec08: Additional 
information received from the investigator 15Dec08. Added events of hypotension, worsened anemia, narcotic 
overdose, thrombocytopenia, leukopenia, and sepsis. Added reporter, laboratory and diagnostic tests, concomitant 
medications, treatment medications, and admission/discharge dates. Updated start date for syncope. Updated 
narrative appropriately. Update 24Dec08: Upon further review of the information received on 15Dec08, amended 
listedness for the event of sepsis to Listed against USPI, Core, and SPC. Update 19Jan09: Additional information 
received from the investigator 12Jan09. Events of syncope and port infection were deleted. Updated narrative 
appropriately.